data.chText: 抽鼻子（尤指哭泣、患感冒等时出声地用鼻子吸气）
data.enText: to breathe air in through your nose in a way that makes a sound, especially when you are crying, have a cold, etc.

data.chText: 我们都感冒了，一个劲地抽鼻子，打喷嚏。
data.enText: We all had colds and couldn't stop sniffing and sneezing.

data.chText: （吸着气）嗅，闻
data.enText: to breathe air in through the nose in order to discover or enjoy the smell of sth

data.chText: 吸着早晨的新鲜空气
data.enText: sniffing the fresh morning air

data.chText: 吸胶毒
data.enText: to sniff glue

data.chText: 那条狗嗅我的鞋。
data.enText: The dog sniffed at my shoes.

data.chText: 抱怨；不以为然地说
data.enText: to say sth in a complaining or disapproving way

data.chText: “要我说，这很难称得上雅致。”她不以为然地说。
data.enText: ‘It's hardly what I'd call elegant,’ she sniffed.
not to be sniffed at

data.chText: 值得认真对待；不可轻视
data.enText: good enough to be accepted or considered seriously

data.chText: 那时候，20元不能不当回事。
data.enText: In those days, $20 was not a sum to be sniffed at.
sniff around/round

data.chText: 探查，打探，访查（秘密信息）
data.enText: to try to find out information about sb/sth, especially secret information

data.chText: 我们不想把记者招来四处打探。
data.enText: We don't want journalists sniffing around.
sniff around/round sb

data.chText: 追求，寻求聘用（某人）
data.enText: to try to get sb as a lover, employee, etc.

data.chText: 一些好莱坞的经纪人一直追着想要他。
data.enText: Hollywood agents have been sniffing around him.
sniff at sth

data.chText: 对…嗤之以鼻（或不屑一顾）
data.enText: to show no interest in or respect for sth
sniff sb/sth↔out

data.chText: 嗅出
data.enText: to discover or find sb/sth by using your sense of smell

data.chText: 这些狗是经过训练的嗅毒犬。
data.enText: The dogs are trained to sniff out drugs.

data.chText: 看出；觉察出
data.enText: to discover or find sb/sth by looking

data.chText: 记者善于发现丑闻。
data.enText: Journalists are good at sniffing out a scandal.

data.chText: 吸气（声）；抽鼻子（声）；嗅；闻
data.enText: an act or the sound of sniffing

data.chText: 她使劲闻了闻香水。
data.enText: She took a deep sniff of the perfume.

data.chText: 我母亲哼了一声，表示不同意。
data.enText: My mother gave a sniff of disapproval.

data.chText: 不多时，他的呜咽变成了啜泣。
data.enText: His sobs soon turned to sniffs.

data.chText: 感觉；察觉
data.enText: an idea of what sth is like or that sth is going to happen

data.chText: 权力在握的感觉使他得意忘形。
data.enText: The sniff of power went to his head.

data.chText: 他们起先气势汹汹，但一看情形不妙立刻软了下来。
data.enText: They make threats but back down at the first sniff of trouble.

data.chText: 微小的可能性
data.enText: a small chance of sth

data.chText: 她根本不可能拿到奖牌。
data.enText: She didn't get even a sniff at a medal.
have a (good) sniff around

data.chText: 仔细检查（某处）
data.enText: to examine a place carefully

trans: 试图抢走（心上人）；企图挖走（员工、客户等）

tr: sensing an odor by inhaling through the nose

example: the sick student was sniffling in the back row

tr: perceive by inhaling through the nose

value.def: When you sniff, you breathe in air through your nose hard enough to make a sound, for example when you are trying not to cry, or in order to show disapproval.

example.ex: She wiped her face and sniffed loudly...
example.tran: 她抹了一把脸，很响地抽着鼻子。

example.ex: Moira looked around and sniffed. 'This place badly needs a decorator.'...
example.tran: 莫伊拉环顾四周，抽了抽鼻子。“这个地方太需要有人来装修一下了。”

example.ex: Then he sniffed. There was a smell of burning...
example.tran: 然后他抽了抽鼻子，发觉有一股烧焦的味道。
他抽着鼻子，把眼泪忍了下去。

example.ex: At last the sobs ceased, to be replaced by sniffs.
example.tran: 最后，啜泣终于止住了，只剩下抽鼻子的声音。

value.tran: (忍住不哭或表示不赞成时)抽鼻子

value.def: If you sniff something or sniff at it, you smell it by sniffing.

example.ex: Suddenly, he stopped and sniffed the air...
example.tran: 他突然停下来，闻了闻空气里的味道。

value.def: You can use sniff to indicate that someone says something in a way that shows their disapproval or contempt.
value.tran: 嗤之以鼻地表示;轻蔑地说

value.def: If you say that something is not to be sniffed at, you think it is very good or worth having. If someone sniffs at something, they do not think it is good enough, or they express their contempt for it.

example.ex: The salary was not to be sniffed at either...
Foreign Office sources sniffed at reports that British troops might be sent.
example.tran: 外交部消息人士对有可能派出英国军队的报道不屑一顾。

value.def: If someone sniffs a substance such as glue, they deliberately breathe in the substance or the gases from it as a drug.

example.ex: He felt light-headed, as if he'd sniffed glue.
example.tran: 他觉得晕乎乎的，好像吸了胶毒一样。

value.def: If you get a sniff of something, you learn or guess that it might be happening or might be near.

example.ex: You know what they'll be like if they get a sniff of a murder investigation...
example.tran: 你知道如果他们嗅到马上会进行谋杀调查会怎么样。

example.ex: Have the Press got a sniff yet?...
example.tran: 新闻界嗅到了一点消息没有？

example.ex: Then, at the first sniff of danger, he was back at his post.
example.tran: 然后，他一嗅到危险的气息，便马上回到自己的岗位。

value.def: If you say that someone has not had a sniff of something, you mean that they have not had even a small chance of getting it.

example.ex: Winterton has never had a sniff of a government job in his entire twenty-one years in parliament.
example.tran: 在国会的整整21年里，温特顿没有得到过任何在政府里工作的机会。
